1
00:00:04,724 --> 00:00:09,163
These descriptions,
they’re not ordinary descriptions.

2
00:00:09,163 --> 00:00:12,999
That’s why whenever 
we repeat them

3
00:00:12,999 --> 00:00:15,239
we should try to do so
with the greatest accuracy.

4
00:00:15,547 --> 00:00:18,662
[Different Tastes of Truth]

5
00:00:19,353 --> 00:00:23,046
Or, if Kṛṣṇa’s pastimes
are being told to children,

6
00:00:23,046 --> 00:00:25,382
they should be accurate;

7
00:00:25,382 --> 00:00:27,249
we shouldn’t make things up,

8
00:00:27,249 --> 00:00:29,593
they should accurately follow
the story.

9
00:00:29,593 --> 00:00:37,149
Because here’s a child
offering themselves to hear these things,

10
00:00:37,241 --> 00:00:38,939
they need to get it right

11
00:00:38,939 --> 00:00:42,415
so that they’ll get
the maximum benefit for it,

12
00:00:42,415 --> 00:00:47,310
because they’re perfectly constructed, 
and in the future,

13
00:00:47,310 --> 00:00:50,529
when they recall hearing these things
in their childhood,

14
00:00:50,529 --> 00:00:55,397
they may have a tendency
to reproduce them accurately.

15
00:00:56,982 --> 00:01:06,779
Bhakti Vinoda Ṭhākur, 
placing emphasis on the pastimes of Kṛṣṇa,

16
00:01:06,779 --> 00:01:10,556
the childhood pastimes of Kṛṣṇa
in Śrīmad Bhāgavatam,

17
00:01:10,556 --> 00:01:13,726
and the pastimes of 
Chaitanya Mahāprabhu.

18
00:01:14,019 --> 00:01:21,383
So in one sense, 
the whole idea is total immersion,

19
00:01:21,952 --> 00:01:27,484
and we have a glimpse 
of that when we hear

20
00:01:28,545 --> 00:01:31,939
from the higher devotees.

21
00:01:31,985 --> 00:01:37,827
And interestingly, 
even the same pastimes

22
00:01:38,365 --> 00:01:46,675
can be described accurately
by great devotees

23
00:01:46,675 --> 00:01:52,337
but still have a different taste 
and quality to the rendering.

24
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:58,115
As we find, in the beginning of
the Bṛhad-bhāgavatāmṛtam,

25
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:04,119
Mahārāj Janamejay
is speaking with Jaimini Ṛṣi,

26
00:02:04,366 --> 00:02:11,719
and he’d just finished 
a Mahābhārata recitation,

27
00:02:12,519 --> 00:02:18,341
and Janamejay says, “I heard this previously
from Vaiśampāyana Ṛṣi”—

28
00:02:19,464 --> 00:02:24,121
this story, 
the Mahābhārata divine story.

29
00:02:25,318 --> 00:02:30,334
He’s saying, “Essentially you’ve told
the same things,

30
00:02:30,826 --> 00:02:35,143
but the way you’ve told it, 
it has a particular

31
00:02:35,389 --> 00:02:39,829
madhura, sweetness,
quality to it,

32
00:02:40,106 --> 00:02:45,220
and your recitation
has awakened in me

33
00:02:45,220 --> 00:02:49,299
a desire for more of 
this madhura sweetness.”

34
00:02:50,426 --> 00:02:52,983
And it’s in response to that,

35
00:02:52,983 --> 00:02:58,984
that Jaimini Ṛṣi begins telling
the Bṛhad-bhāgavatāmṛtam.

36
00:02:58,984 --> 00:03:03,756
So it shows it’s not merely
the transfer of information

37
00:03:03,756 --> 00:03:08,872
or story, "Oh, I heard that story”,
but how it is told,

38
00:03:08,872 --> 00:03:14,442
the way Vṛndāvan Dās Ṭhākur
is telling some pastimes,

39
00:03:14,442 --> 00:03:18,348
and similar pastimes 
are being told by Kavirāj Goswāmī.

40
00:03:18,886 --> 00:03:24,971
Out of fear of committing 
maryādā-vyatikram,

41
00:03:24,971 --> 00:03:31,654
impertinently surpassing 
the predecessor,

42
00:03:31,824 --> 00:03:35,414
Kavirāj Goswāmī would say,
“What Vṛndāvan Dās has described,

43
00:03:35,644 --> 00:03:37,980
it would be an aparādh 
to describe the same thing,

44
00:03:37,980 --> 00:03:41,199
but if there’s some aspect
that was not described,

45
00:03:41,199 --> 00:03:43,637
I’ll describe that.”

46
00:03:43,637 --> 00:03:47,036
He says that humbly, 
but we know from Śrīla Guru Mahārāj,

47
00:03:47,036 --> 00:03:51,595
Vṛndāvan Dās Ṭhākur, 
when we worship Chaitanya Bhāgavat,

48
00:03:51,610 --> 00:03:57,501
is from the perspective of 
a cowherd boy—sakhya rasa;

49
00:03:57,762 --> 00:04:03,329
Chaitanya-charitāmṛtam is an exclusively
madhura-rasa literature.

50
00:04:04,329 --> 00:04:08,466
Just like in my first actual meeting with 
Śrīla Guru Mahārāj,

51
00:04:08,466 --> 00:04:11,588
where Kṛṣṇadās Bābājī Mahārāj 
took myself

52
00:04:11,588 --> 00:04:16,491
and Bhakti Abhay Nārāyaṇ Mahārāj up to
the lotus feet of Guru Mahārāj,

53
00:04:16,716 --> 00:04:19,628
at one point,
Bhakti Abhay Nārāyaṇ Mahārāj

54
00:04:19,628 --> 00:04:22,746
said to him, “I find I’m more attracted

55
00:04:22,746 --> 00:04:26,765
to Chaitanya-charitāmṛtam
than Śrīmad Bhāgavatam.”

56
00:04:26,888 --> 00:04:29,177
Like, a bold statement.

57
00:04:29,331 --> 00:04:36,425
But Guru Mahārāj 
just responded very matter-of-factly,

58
00:04:36,425 --> 00:04:42,069
saying, “Of course,” he said, 
“because Śrīmad Bhāgavatam

59
00:04:42,069 --> 00:04:45,997
presents rasa—takes us from
the plane of ontology to rasa—

60
00:04:45,997 --> 00:04:50,644
but in gradual development, 
culminating in madhura-rasa in the 10th canto,

61
00:04:50,644 --> 00:04:53,147
whereas Chaitanya-charitāmṛtam

62
00:04:53,147 --> 00:04:55,942
is an exclusively 
madhura-rasa literature,

63
00:04:55,942 --> 00:04:58,318
so naturally that is
your preference.”

64
00:04:58,318 --> 00:05:00,253
And I was saying,
“It is?”

